@article{Lall2006c,
abstract = {Resumo O presente trabalho analisa os efeitos da legisla{\c{c}}{\~{a}}o de zoneamento e de regula{\c{c}}{\~{o}}es de densidade sobre a oferta de habita{\c{c}}{\~{o}}es formais e sobre a forma{\c{c}}{\~{a}}o de favelas nas cidades brasileiras entre 1980 e 2000. Verifica-se, em particular, a performance das cidades que reduziram a subdivis{\~{a}}o dos lotes (tamanho do lote m{\'{i}}nimo) do estipulado em lei federal (125 m2). Desenvolve-se um modelo de oferta habitacional formal e de forma{\c{c}}{\~{a}}o de favelas em que o crescimento populacional {\'{e}} end{\'{o}}geno e a decis{\~{a}}o de migrar dos agentes {\'{e}} influenciada por varia{\c{c}}{\~{o}}es na regula{\c{c}}{\~{a}}o urban{\'{i}}stica entre cidades. O trabalho averigua que a elasticidade da oferta de habita{\c{c}}{\~{o}}es formais {\'{e}} muito baixa, compar{\'{a}}vel {\`{a}} de pa{\'{i}}ses como Mal{\'{a}}sia e Cor{\'{e}}ia do Sul, cujos mercados habitacionais s{\~{a}}o altamente regulados. A an{\'{a}}lise mostra que (a) o planejamento do uso do solo melhora o desempenho do mercado habitacional formal e estimula a resposta do referido {\`{a}} demanda existente; (b) a flexibiliza{\c{c}}{\~{a}}o de regula{\c{c}}{\~{o}}es de lote m{\'{i}}nimo aumenta a oferta de resid{\^{e}}ncias formais, mas tamb{\'{e}}m {\'{e}} acompanhada por um crescimento populacional mais elevado. Constatou-se que o crescimento populacional foi superior {\`{a}} resposta da oferta de habita{\c{c}}{\~{o}}es formais e, como resultado, gerou-se um crescimento da forma{\c{c}}{\~{a}}o de favelas. Isto sugere que pol{\'{i}}ticas p{\'{u}}blicas que visem reduzir as barreiras de acesso {\`{a}} habita{\c{c}}{\~{a}}o devem ser seguidas por instrumentos com o intuito de relaxar distor{\c{c}}{\~{o}}es pr{\'{e}}-existentes no mercado habitacional. Na aus{\^{e}}ncia dessas medidas, regula{\c{c}}{\~{o}}es urban{\'{i}}sticas mais flex{\'{i}}veis podem exacerbar o problema de forma{\c{c}}{\~{a}}o de favelas. Abstract In this paper, we examine the effects of land use zoning and density regulations on formal housing supply and slum formation across Brazilian cities between 1980 and 2000. In particular we look at the performance of cities that have lowered land subdivision (minimum lot size) regulation from the federally mandated 125 m 2 . We develop a model of formal housing supply and slum formation where population growth is endogenous and household migration decisions are influenced by inter city variations in land regulations. We find that the elasticity of formal housing supply in Brazil is very low, and comparable to those found in Malaysia and South Korea, which have highly regulated housing markets. Our analysis of land regulations shows that (a) general purpose zoning and land use planning improves performance of the housing market and stimulates formal sector housing response; (b) lowering minimum lot size regulations increases housing supply but is also accompanied by higher population growth. We find that population growth is faster than the formal housing supply response, leading to an increase in slum formation. This suggests that policies that aim to reduce barriers for access to land need to be accompanied by instruments that relax pre-existing distortions in the land market. In the absence of these measures, pro poor land regulations may in fact exacerbate the slum formation problem.},
